      <h2>Understanding Tablespoon Measurements</h2>
      <p>
        The tablespoon is a kitchen workhorse measurement, bridging the gap between teaspoons and cups. One US tablespoon equals approximately 14.787 mL, which is exactly 3 teaspoons or half a fluid ounce. Tablespoons are used for measuring oils, sauces, butter, spices in larger quantities, and any ingredient too large for a teaspoon but too small for a cup.
      </p>
      <p>
        Be aware that tablespoon sizes vary internationally. A US tablespoon is 14.787 mL, an Australian (metric) tablespoon is 20 mL, and a UK tablespoon is approximately 17.758 mL. This converter uses the US tablespoon standard but converts to all common volume units instantly.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Common Tablespoon Conversions</h2>
      <p>
        The most frequently needed conversions: 1 US tablespoon = 14.787 mL, 1 tablespoon = 3 teaspoons, 2 tablespoons = 1 fluid ounce, 16 tablespoons = 1 US cup. For butter, 1 tablespoon equals roughly 14 grams or half an ounce. These quick references cover most everyday cooking needs.
      </p>

      <h3>Tablespoons and Cups</h3>
      <p>
        There are exactly 16 US tablespoons in one US cup. This makes fractional cup measurements easy to express in tablespoons: a quarter cup is 4 tablespoons, a third cup is about 5 and a third tablespoons, and half a cup is 8 tablespoons. When a recipe calls for an odd fraction of a cup, switching to tablespoons often makes measuring more practical.
      </p>

      <h3>US vs. Metric vs. UK Tablespoons</h3>
      <p>
        The US tablespoon (14.787 mL) is the most commonly referenced in American and Canadian recipes. The Australian metric tablespoon (20 mL) is about 35% larger. The UK tablespoon (17.758 mL) falls in between. When converting recipes between countries, this difference can affect the outcome, especially for concentrated ingredients like vanilla extract, salt, or baking powder.
      </p>
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How many mL are in a tablespoon?</h3>
      <p>
        One US tablespoon equals approximately 14.787 mL. A metric tablespoon, used in Australia and some other countries, is exactly 20 mL. A UK tablespoon is approximately 17.758 mL. This converter uses the US tablespoon (14.787 mL), which is the most common standard in American recipes.
      </p>

      <h3>How many tablespoons are in a cup?</h3>
      <p>
        There are 16 US tablespoons in one US cup. This means a quarter cup is 4 tablespoons, a third cup is about 5.33 tablespoons, and half a cup is 8 tablespoons. These conversions are essential for scaling recipes up or down.
      </p>

      <h3>How many teaspoons are in a tablespoon?</h3>
      <p>
        There are 3 US teaspoons in one US tablespoon. This means half a tablespoon is 1.5 teaspoons. This is one of the most commonly needed kitchen conversions when a recipe calls for a fraction of a tablespoon.
      </p>

      <h3>How many tablespoons are in a fluid ounce?</h3>
      <p>
        There are 2 US tablespoons in one US fluid ounce. This means 1 tablespoon is half a fluid ounce (approximately 14.79 mL). For example, a standard shot glass of 1.5 fluid ounces holds 3 tablespoons.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between a US and metric tablespoon?</h3>
      <p>
        A US tablespoon is approximately 14.787 mL, while a metric tablespoon (used in Australia, for example) is exactly 20 mL. The difference is significant — a metric tablespoon is about 35% larger than a US one. When following Australian or British recipes, this distinction matters for accuracy.
      </p>

